## Wooten Spring Park aims to be “a park first” near Cloudcroft

A planned 45-acre development near Cloudcroft is being pitched as something broader than a traditional RV park, with its developers saying Wooten Spring Park is intended to function as a public-facing mountain destination with trails, recreation, events and overnight lodging.

“So our vision is a really awesome park,” one of the developers said during the discussion. “Yes, it’s going to be an RV park, a big part of it, or at least half of it, but that’s not like our main vision.” He continued: “Our vision is to have a place where people can come [by] RV and stay and enjoy amenities. But also a place where the public can stop in and go to our welcome center, to our gift shop, play on our pickleball courts, enjoy our orchard and our park, and, you know, potentially have live music one day.” He added, “Our overall vision is just to really create a destination, not just an RV Park.”

That idea was echoed elsewhere in the conversation. One participant summarized the concept this way: “At its core, it’s an RV retreat, but it’s designed to feel more like a mountain park than a typical RV park.” Later, one of the developers offered the shortest version of the same point: “We’re a park first.”

The project’s public-facing component appears central to that vision. “We do plan to open it to the public,” one developer said. “With day passes.” He said the goal is to create a place that serves “both the overnight guests as well as the local ones,” and added that the team hopes to host “some music events and different things that we do for the community over time.”

The amenities discussed in the meeting suggest a project designed to offer more than lodging. Plans mentioned in the conversation include RV sites on about half the property, a smaller tent camping area, about two miles of trails, a half-acre recreational pond, orchard access, a welcome center, convenience retail, branded merchandise, pickleball courts and a music stage. The team also said it is considering beer sales, though it noted that the logistics are still being worked out.

Several of the quotes offered a more detailed picture of how the property might function. “We have two miles of trails along the stream and around backing national forest,” one developer said. He also described “a beautiful half-acre pond” that the team is working to shape into “a beautiful, fun, recreational park where people can paddle board and splash in the water a little bit.” Looking to the orchard, he added: “We have our orchard with apples and pears, so definitely come visit us during those seasons.”

On events and recreation, the tone was similarly expansive. “We plan on having a music stage,” one developer said, adding, “we hope to have some music events.” On pickleball, the team said it is hoping for “three to six” courts, with one participant noting they had already “measured out a footprint to have six.” Another possible amenity remains under review: “We do hope to have beer,” one developer said, before adding that “there’s some extra logistics there that we’re not quite sure about.”

The property’s identity is also tied to local history. In the meeting, the site was described as the former Mountain Park trout farm, associated with the Tony Llama family. The developers said the project takes its name from Wooten Spring, which one speaker described as “the original spring that was the last stop for the steam engine train on the way up to Cloudcroft to fill up with water.” He called it “beautiful pristine water” that still “gushes water right out of the side of the mountain.”

The naming reaches back even further. One speaker said the spring was named after “Benjamin Wooten, who purchased the property with his wife in the 1800s.” He added that “that whole area was called Wooten, New Mexico, and had the first post office before High Rolls even had a post office.”

The development team includes Bryce and Justin, along with their wives, Rihanna and Marianne. Bryce was identified in the meeting as being with Zuni Electric in Alamogordo. According to the discussion, the group had been exploring business ideas together for some time and had spent about a year looking for the right property before moving on this one. They said they had first made an offer on another property, then shifted to this parcel when the opportunity emerged.

One participant described the site as “a one-of-a-kind parcel,” while another pointed to the appeal of “that much flat acreage five minutes from Cloudcroft” with “tons of springs on it.” The team also emphasized that the property’s water source is its own. “We’re not taking water from anyone else,” one developer said. “We’re using our own.”

The timeline discussed in the meeting points to a possible opening in summer 2027, pending permits. “We’re hoping for a one-year turnaround on this build out,” one developer said. “We’re looking at the summer of ’27.” He added that state permits are among the details that could slow the schedule.

For now, the project is entering an early public phase. The team said it plans to direct interest to its website and Facebook page, build email signups and use construction updates as part of its storytelling strategy. One developer said the hope is that people will begin “following the construction progress,” while another participant noted the project offers “a lot of different little stories” to tell over time.

Taken together, the quotes from the discussion show a project trying to define itself in broader terms than a typical RV development. As one of the developers put it, “We’re a park first.”

